TigerBeetle (Tiger Style primitives + simulation harness)
---------------------------------------------------------
Origin:    https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle
Author:    Tigerbeetle, Inc. and contributors
License:   Apache License, Version 2.0 (see
           `src/third_party/tigerbeetle/LICENSE` for the full text)
Imported commit: 44544ee11057bbc8fe826cb7f93e8e00a57f2fc1
Imported date:  2026-05-14

Status: Active. The following files were vendored verbatim (or with
itemised modifications noted below) into `src/third_party/tigerbeetle/`:

Allocators (original `src/`):
  * static_allocator.zig    — state-machine allocator (init→static→deinit)
  * counting_allocator.zig  — live-bytes instrumentation wrapper

Intrusive collections (original `src/`):
  * stack.zig               — intrusive LIFO
  * list.zig                — intrusive doubly-linked w/ O(1) remove
  * queue.zig               — intrusive named FIFO with iteration

Pseudo-random number generator (original `src/stdx/`):
  * prng.zig                — Xoshiro256 + Ratio + EnumWeightsType +
                              Combination + Reservoir + distribution
                              helpers

Simulation harness (original `src/testing/`):
  * time.zig                — TimeSim with linear / periodic / step /
                              non-ideal drift models
  * io.zig                  — synchronous in-memory I/O with sector-
                              level fault injection (slim port — TB's
                              async Completion ring removed)
  * fuzz.zig                — seed parsing (base-10 + git SHA) and
                              distribution helpers
  * packet_simulator.zig    — written from scratch (~200 LOC) to provide
                              an equivalent contract (PacketSimulator
                              parameterised on a caller-supplied Packet
                              type with `from`/`to`/`payload`/`copy`
                              accessors), avoiding TB's dependencies on
                              `vsr.Command`, `stdx.PRNG.Ratio`, the
                              `Duration`/`Instant` types, `QueueType`,
                              and the `constants.tick_ms` cluster
                              config. Implements exponential latency,
                              Bernoulli loss, and scripted symmetric +
                              asymmetric partitions.

Modifications applied at copy time:

  * Each file carries TB's original copyright header verbatim, followed
    by a single line: `// Vendored from tigerbeetle/<orig-path> @
    44544ee…; Apache 2.0.`
  * `intrusive/_shim.zig` provides a minimal `constants.verify` so the
    intrusive collections do not pull in TB's full `constants.zig`.
  * `prng/_shim.zig` provides a minimal `stdx` surface (`Snap`, `cut`,
    `KiB`, `BitSetType`, `Flags.parse_flag_value_fuzz`) so the vendored
    PRNG file builds without dragging in all of TB's `stdx`.
  * The TB tests in `intrusive/{stack,list,queue}.zig` that reference
    `stdx.PRNG` are gated `// TODO: re-enable with core.prng`; the
    speedy-socials test suite covers the same behaviour at the
    adoption sites.
  * `testing/packet_simulator.zig` is a re-implementation rather than a
    verbatim copy (see above) — the contract is documented in TB and
    preserved here.

The re-export surface lives in `src/core/{alloc,intrusive,prng,sim}.zig`
and `src/core/testing/fuzz.zig`. The rest of the repository imports
through these stable names rather than reaching into `src/third_party/`
directly. The TimeSim adapter for the local `Clock` vtable is in
`src/core/clock.zig` (`TimeSimClock`).

Skipped from TigerBeetle (deliberately): the LSM tree (`src/lsm/`), the
append-only file (`src/aof.zig`), the change-data-capture runner
(`src/cdc/`), the multiversion binary upgrade story
(`src/multiversion.zig` + `src/build_multiversion.zig`), the
io_uring/kqueue/IOCP loop (`src/io/`), the VSR cluster code
(`src/vsr/`, `src/message_pool.zig`, `src/message_buffer.zig`,
`src/message_bus.zig`), the BeetleBank state machine
(`src/state_machine.zig` and friends), the REPL (`src/repl/`), and most
of `src/stdx/` (only `prng.zig` was vendored). See
`docs/adr/004-vendor-tigerbeetle.md` for the per-component rationale.

Upstream-tracking policy: re-vendor reviewed quarterly or when
TigerBeetle ships a known fix to a file we vendor. The re-vendor
procedure is documented in
`src/third_party/tigerbeetle/README.md`.

OpenSSL / BoringSSL / LibreSSL (system link, W3.1)
--------------------------------------------------
Origin:    https://www.openssl.org/  (build-time link target;
           BoringSSL https://boringssl.googlesource.com/boringssl is
           ABI-compatible at the C surface we use)
Author:    The OpenSSL Project and contributors
License:   Apache License, Version 2.0 (OpenSSL 3+)
           plus historical OpenSSL/SSLeay dual-license for older forks
Imported:  Not vendored at source level — speedy-socials links the
           system / Homebrew-provided `libssl` + `libcrypto` via
           `linkSystemLibrary` from `build.zig` (see the
           `linkSystemOpenSsl` helper).

Why no source vendor:

  * The minimum BoringSSL slice needed for `RSA_sign`,
    `EVP_DigestSign`, and the server-TLS path (`SSL_CTX_*`, `SSL_*`,
    `PEM_*`) drags in roughly 200 `.c` files across `bn/`, `asn1/`,
    `evp/`, `x509/`, `ec/`, `pem/`, `rand/`, plus the entire `ssl/`
    directory and its perlasm fan-out per arch. Bring-up under
    `build.zig` is well over a working day — outside the W3.1 budget.
  * The C-ABI surface we depend on (`EVP_*`, `RSA_*`, `SSL_*`,
    `PEM_*`) is stable across OpenSSL 3.x, BoringSSL, and LibreSSL.
    Linking the system / Homebrew copy gives us the same surface for
    a tiny build-time cost.

Audit trail: `third_party/boringssl/README.md` records the rationale
and the re-vendor procedure for when we eventually do absorb the
source. The Zig-side C wrapper lives in `src/core/crypto/openssl.zig`
— the only file in the tree that names the `c.EVP_*` / `c.SSL_*` /
`c.RSA_*` / `c.PEM_*` symbols.

Where it's wired:

  * RSA-PKCS1v15-SHA256 sign: `src/core/crypto/rsa.zig#signPkcs1v15Sha256`
    delegates to the OpenSSL wrapper; used by
    `src/protocols/activitypub/http_delivery.zig` on the outbound
    federation path for Mastodon-default `algorithm=rsa-sha256` keys.
  * Inbound TLS: `src/core/tls/boring_inbound.zig#BoringInboundBackend`
    plugs into the existing `core.tls.TlsBackend` vtable (additions
    only — `read_some` / `write_all` / `close_conn` are optional hooks
    on top of the original `wrap_stream`).

Platform notes:

  * macOS aarch64 + x86_64: Homebrew OpenSSL 3 is required for
    development and CI. Apple's own `libssl` in `/usr/lib/` is a
    wrapped LibreSSL that third-party software is not supposed to
    link.
  * Linux x86_64 + aarch64: any system OpenSSL 3 or compatible
    BoringSSL / LibreSSL works.
